<TITLE> Bangladesh signs Trans-Asian Railway deal </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 11 (bdnews24.com) -- Bangladesh has signed the agreement on Trans-Asian Railway Network, an official said Sunday. Ismat Jahan, ambassador and permanent representative of Bangladesh to the United Nations, signed the "Intergovernmental Agreement on the Trans-Asian Railway Network," at the UN Headquarters in New York. The Bangladesh mission in New York confirmed the news to bdnews24.com. With Bangladesh on board, the number of signatories to the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP)-sponsored agreement reached 20. The agreement will enable Bangladesh to expand its rail communications with other Asian countries and Europe. The railway network covers 28 countries, including a stretch of 22,600km in South Asia, Iran and Turkey in the southern corridor that stretches from Kunming in China to Kapikule in Bulgaria. Eighteen countries initially signed the agreement on November 10, 2006 in Jakarta, Indonesia. bdn
